1
00:00:04,905 --> 00:00:06,206
Hey, there, I'm Guy Fieri,
and we're rolling out,

2
00:00:06,306 --> 00:00:09,810
looking for America's greatest
diners, drive‐ins, and dives.

3
00:00:09,910 --> 00:00:11,578
This trip...
Hey!

4
00:00:11,678 --> 00:00:13,614
...we're digging up
some island treasures...

5
00:00:13,714 --> 00:00:15,148
I like the beginning
of this deal.

6
00:00:15,248 --> 00:00:17,017
...and discovering
a desert oasis...

7
00:00:17,117 --> 00:00:18,919
Oh, this is
that kind of place.

8
00:00:19,019 --> 00:00:21,121
...which is actually in
Palm Desert, California...

9
00:00:21,221 --> 00:00:22,422
Well played,
my friend.

10
00:00:22,523 --> 00:00:25,025
...where breakfast and lunch
is savory and sweet...

11
00:00:25,125 --> 00:00:26,927
You won't like these.
Never come here.

12
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:28,128
[ Laughs ]

13
00:00:28,228 --> 00:00:29,129
...and in Maui...

14
00:00:29,229 --> 00:00:30,564
Okay.
I'm down with it.

15
00:00:30,664 --> 00:00:33,466
...a place that's gluten‐free
and full of flavor...

16
00:00:33,567 --> 00:00:34,635
That's crazy.

17
00:00:34,735 --> 00:00:36,637
...plus, a funky joint
in Virginia Beach...

18
00:00:36,737 --> 00:00:38,672
I like the way this guy works.
He's got his own style.

19
00:00:38,772 --> 00:00:40,507
... where things get
a little out of control

20
00:00:40,607 --> 00:00:42,375
[ Laughs ]
with the Caribbean.

21
00:00:42,475 --> 00:00:44,878
The food's great, but come down
for the floor show.

22
00:00:44,978 --> 00:00:47,080
That's all right here,
right now,

23
00:00:47,180 --> 00:00:49,315
on "Diners, Drive‐Ins &amp; Dives."

24
00:00:49,415 --> 00:00:58,992
♪♪♪

25
00:00:59,092 --> 00:01:02,235
♪♪♪

26
00:01:02,335 --> 00:01:03,403
Hey, excuse me.
Excuse me.

27
00:01:03,504 --> 00:01:06,907
Can you tell me
where Wilma &amp; Frieda's is?

28
00:01:07,007 --> 00:01:08,975
That way?
Thank you.

29
00:01:09,075 --> 00:01:12,278
FIERI:
Well, I guess the '68 can't
pull right up to this one.

30
00:01:12,378 --> 00:01:14,214
I'm here at The Gardens
on El Paseo

31
00:01:14,314 --> 00:01:16,282
in Palm Desert,
California,

32
00:01:16,382 --> 00:01:17,784
and I'm looking for
this funky joint

33
00:01:17,884 --> 00:01:20,320
where a brother and sister
have teamed up to give you

34
00:01:20,420 --> 00:01:23,123
an eclectic breakfast and lunch
experience you won't forget.

35
00:01:23,223 --> 00:01:25,325
This is Wilma &amp; Frieda.

36
00:01:27,260 --> 00:01:28,929
Blackberry custard
French toast.

37
00:01:29,029 --> 00:01:30,463
We like to think of it
as the rising star

38
00:01:30,564 --> 00:01:32,666
of the Coachella Valley
when it comes to restaurants.

39
00:01:32,766 --> 00:01:34,067
Meatloaf
and eggs over easy.

40
00:01:34,167 --> 00:01:37,370
Comfort food,
but with a delectable twist.

41
00:01:37,470 --> 00:01:39,506
FIERI: The kind of food
that made Kelly McFall

42
00:01:39,606 --> 00:01:40,641
ditch her corporate life

43
00:01:40,741 --> 00:01:42,576
and recruit her brother,
Craig Alexander,

44
00:01:42,676 --> 00:01:45,245
to open a joint named
after their grandmothers.

45
00:01:45,345 --> 00:01:48,582
And now they're dishing
down‐home to a high‐end crowd.

46
00:01:48,682 --> 00:01:51,484
El Paseo's kind of known as
the Rodeo Drive of the desert.

47
00:01:51,585 --> 00:01:52,819
Oh, this is
that kind of place.

48
00:01:52,919 --> 00:01:54,888
We were kind of
the casual place.

49
00:01:54,988 --> 00:01:56,489
The meatloaf's ready,
Chef.

50
00:01:56,590 --> 00:01:57,658
So, who am I
cooking with?

51
00:01:57,758 --> 00:01:58,625
Chad's our chef.

52
00:01:58,725 --> 00:01:59,893
He is amazing.
Okay.

53
00:01:59,993 --> 00:02:01,868
And we have Camilla
as our pastry chef.

54
00:02:01,968 --> 00:02:02,936
So I get to cook
with both of them?

55
00:02:03,036 --> 00:02:04,605
SPEARS: Short‐rib melt
on sourdough.

56
00:02:04,705 --> 00:02:06,306
The short‐rib melt
is incredible.

57
00:02:06,406 --> 00:02:07,407
MAN:
You can't get it anywhere else.

58
00:02:07,508 --> 00:02:09,876
It's definitely
an experience in itself.

59
00:02:09,976 --> 00:02:11,377
Well,
what are we making?

60
00:02:11,477 --> 00:02:13,346
SPEARS: We're going to
braise the short rib
for the short‐rib melt.

61
00:02:13,446 --> 00:02:15,882
So, we start out with
the boneless short rib,

62
00:02:15,982 --> 00:02:18,985
black peppercorn,
garlic cloves, bay leaves.

63
00:02:19,085 --> 00:02:19,986
A lot of bay leaves.

64
00:02:20,086 --> 00:02:21,888
Brown thyme,
kosher salt,

65
00:02:21,988 --> 00:02:24,224
a whole gallon
of Burgundy red wine.
Burgundy?

66
00:02:24,324 --> 00:02:25,892
Is it 'cause
it's "out‐of‐the‐box"?

67
00:02:25,992 --> 00:02:27,193
[ Laughs ]

68
00:02:27,293 --> 00:02:28,494
Mirepoix.

69
00:02:28,595 --> 00:02:29,930
Now you're going to get
all splashy‐splashy, Chef.

70
00:02:30,030 --> 00:02:31,397
All your blue shirts
get splashed.

71
00:02:31,497 --> 00:02:32,465
Are you a fan of me?

72
00:02:32,566 --> 00:02:34,134
Yeah, I'm a fan of all
of your blue shirts.

73
00:02:34,234 --> 00:02:35,435
You've got some issues,
son.

74
00:02:35,536 --> 00:02:36,903
This is a strong beef base,

75
00:02:37,003 --> 00:02:39,239
and we braise it overnight
at 250 degrees.

76
00:02:39,339 --> 00:02:40,541
I like the way
this is going.

77
00:02:40,641 --> 00:02:41,742
All right, boss,
what are we into now?

78
00:02:41,842 --> 00:02:43,677
We are making
pickled red onions.

79
00:02:43,777 --> 00:02:45,111
Red wine vinegar.
Water.

80
00:02:45,211 --> 00:02:46,346
A whole bunch
of coriander.

81
00:02:46,446 --> 00:02:48,448
Black peppercorn,
crushed red pepper flakes,

82
00:02:48,549 --> 00:02:50,316
Bay leaf.
You and your bay leaf!

83
00:02:50,416 --> 00:02:51,785
It's like me
and my blue shirt.

84
00:02:51,885 --> 00:02:52,919
Huh?

85
00:02:53,019 --> 00:02:53,954
Kosher salt.

86
00:02:54,054 --> 00:02:55,288
I let it come to a boil.

87
00:02:55,388 --> 00:02:58,158
Onions go in, steep for
an hour and a half.

88
00:02:58,258 --> 00:02:59,392
Short ribs are
finished braising.

89
00:02:59,492 --> 00:03:02,235
That is pull‐apart
short rib all day long.

90
00:03:02,335 --> 00:03:03,069
Right?

91
00:03:03,169 --> 00:03:05,506
Strain the <i>jus.</i>

92
00:03:05,606 --> 00:03:06,807
We're going to
mix the mirepoix.

93
00:03:06,907 --> 00:03:07,841
[ Whirring ]

94
00:03:07,941 --> 00:03:09,743
That is music to my ears.

95
00:03:09,843 --> 00:03:12,312
And I reincorporate
it back into the meat.

96
00:03:12,412 --> 00:03:13,980
Ohh!

97
00:03:14,080 --> 00:03:15,481
Now we start
to make this melt.

98
00:03:15,582 --> 00:03:17,918
I put oil down,
typically sourdough bread.
All right.

99
00:03:18,018 --> 00:03:21,187
Monterey Jack cheese,
6‐ounce portion of short rib,

100
00:03:21,287 --> 00:03:22,222
pickled red onions.

101
00:03:22,322 --> 00:03:23,657
Sauté the arugula
right behind it.

102
00:03:23,757 --> 00:03:24,858
Got it.

103
00:03:24,958 --> 00:03:26,359
Cook it all up.
Add it together.

104
00:03:26,459 --> 00:03:32,799
♪♪♪

105
00:03:32,899 --> 00:03:35,135
Nice move!
That's like Fonzie, dude.

106
00:03:35,235 --> 00:03:36,570
This is a Fonz move.

107
00:03:38,304 --> 00:03:39,640
"Yo, Cunningham!"

108
00:03:39,740 --> 00:03:40,874
Short rib's tender.

109
00:03:40,974 --> 00:03:42,242
Arugula is
a really nice touch.

110
00:03:42,342 --> 00:03:43,777
But the kicker that makes me
want to take another bite

111
00:03:43,877 --> 00:03:45,078
of this sandwich
each time is what?

112
00:03:45,178 --> 00:03:46,412
Pickled red onion?

113
00:03:46,513 --> 00:03:49,149
This guy's got it.
Thank you.

114
00:03:49,249 --> 00:03:51,451
Well played, my friend.
Give me one more Fonzie.

115
00:03:51,552 --> 00:03:53,053
"Hey‐y‐y‐y!"

116
00:03:55,021 --> 00:03:56,590
It's got
a lot of flavor.

117
00:03:56,690 --> 00:03:58,458
You can really taste,
like, the wine in there.

118
00:03:58,559 --> 00:04:00,794
It's so moist, and the meat
is just amazing.

119
00:04:00,894 --> 00:04:02,302
You don't hear
"moist" enough.
You don't.

120
00:04:02,402 --> 00:04:04,370
I'm for more "moist."
[ Laughs ]

121
00:04:04,470 --> 00:04:05,371
The Hand says he is.

122
00:04:05,471 --> 00:04:06,540
Well,
save room for dessert.

123
00:04:06,640 --> 00:04:08,609
WOMAN: The pastry selection
is amazing.

124
00:04:08,709 --> 00:04:11,377
I've grabbed cookies and cake
pops and things for my kids.

125
00:04:11,477 --> 00:04:14,480
I've had several breakfast tarts
here, and they're all delicious.

126
00:04:14,581 --> 00:04:16,249
Tell me if I get
sugar on my face.

127
00:04:16,349 --> 00:04:18,785
It's got really great
fruity filling.

128
00:04:18,885 --> 00:04:20,186
Very nostalgic.

129
00:04:20,286 --> 00:04:22,723
So, today, we're making
the Wilma &amp; Frieda
breakfast tart.

130
00:04:22,823 --> 00:04:23,857
Okay.
Let's get into it.

131
00:04:23,957 --> 00:04:26,026
We're going to start
with the blueberry compote.

132
00:04:26,126 --> 00:04:27,528
I got fresh blueberries,

133
00:04:27,628 --> 00:04:30,130
some lemon juice,
and granulated sugar.

134
00:04:30,230 --> 00:04:31,565
We're going to let
that cook down.

135
00:04:31,665 --> 00:04:34,133
In the meantime,
we're going to make a slurry.
Okay.

136
00:04:34,233 --> 00:04:35,669
So this is cornstarch
and water.

137
00:04:35,769 --> 00:04:36,970
There we go.

138
00:04:37,070 --> 00:04:39,072
It's going to get thick, and
then it's going to cool down,

139
00:04:39,172 --> 00:04:40,941
and we're going to use
that in our breakfast tart.

140
00:04:41,041 --> 00:04:42,042
We're going to make
the dough now?

141
00:04:42,142 --> 00:04:43,076
Yes.
Awesome.

142
00:04:43,176 --> 00:04:44,144
Did you notice
my blue shirt?

143
00:04:44,244 --> 00:04:45,946
Yes, I did.
Thank you.

144
00:04:46,046 --> 00:04:47,413
Great shirt.

145
00:04:47,514 --> 00:04:51,217
All‐purpose flour, sugar,
kosher salt, nutmeg,

146
00:04:51,317 --> 00:04:54,454
some vanilla extract,
shortening, and butter.

147
00:04:54,555 --> 00:04:55,789
So we're making gravel.

148
00:04:55,889 --> 00:04:57,490
Yes.
And we have ice water.

149
00:04:57,591 --> 00:04:58,925
So, this is all going
to pull together,

150
00:04:59,025 --> 00:05:00,561
and we're going
to roll it out.

151
00:05:00,661 --> 00:05:02,002
Don't get any of that
on my blue shirt.

152
00:05:02,102 --> 00:05:04,638
Don't you start!
I won't, I won't.

153
00:05:04,738 --> 00:05:07,307
All right.
Down to about a centimeter.

154
00:05:07,407 --> 00:05:09,309
And then we're going to use
a pastry cutter.

155
00:05:09,409 --> 00:05:10,777
Time to party.

156
00:05:10,877 --> 00:05:12,345
And we go the other way.

157
00:05:12,445 --> 00:05:15,248
And this is where
the blueberry compote comes in.

158
00:05:15,348 --> 00:05:18,585
And we take one more piece
and some egg wash,

159
00:05:18,685 --> 00:05:21,054
and we paint it
like Picasso.

160
00:05:21,154 --> 00:05:21,988
Ooh. Okay.

161
00:05:22,088 --> 00:05:23,690
And we use
a pastry crimper here.

162
00:05:23,790 --> 00:05:25,225
We got to make sure
we seal it.

163
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:26,527
That's going to
glue it shut.
Yes.

164
00:05:26,627 --> 00:05:27,728
What are we
baking these at?

165
00:05:27,828 --> 00:05:28,795
350.
For how long?

166
00:05:28,895 --> 00:05:30,330
10 minutes, and we're
going to pull it out,

167
00:05:30,430 --> 00:05:32,298
put milk on it, and put it back
in for 10 minutes.

168
00:05:32,398 --> 00:05:33,867
And that
creates the glaze?
Yes.

169
00:05:33,967 --> 00:05:36,169
Dig it!
Learning something today.

170
00:05:36,269 --> 00:05:37,904
Pick a card ‐‐ any card.
This one.

171
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:39,172
You're playing lead dog
on this?

172
00:05:39,272 --> 00:05:40,373
You're in my house.

173
00:05:40,473 --> 00:05:41,575
Ooh!

174
00:05:41,675 --> 00:05:42,743
All right, if that's the one
you think I want.

175
00:05:42,843 --> 00:05:45,245
This is our frosting here.

176
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:46,412
Whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa!

177
00:05:46,513 --> 00:05:47,581
Sprinkles!
What happened?

178
00:05:47,681 --> 00:05:49,816
This is a sprinkles.

179
00:05:49,916 --> 00:05:54,320
We finish it with powdered sugar
and some fresh blueberries.

180
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:55,488
Good seller?
Yes.

181
00:05:55,589 --> 00:05:59,826
♪♪♪

182
00:05:59,926 --> 00:06:01,868
Oh, you won't like these.
Never come here.

183
00:06:01,968 --> 00:06:03,203
[ Laughs ]

184
00:06:03,303 --> 00:06:04,738
That's ridiculous.

185
00:06:04,838 --> 00:06:07,808
It's like shortbread
meets awesome piecrust

186
00:06:07,908 --> 00:06:09,409
meets a morning
breakfast tart.

187
00:06:10,877 --> 00:06:13,113
Wow! The compote in the middle
is really great.

188
00:06:13,213 --> 00:06:14,681
That's the key to it.

189
00:06:14,781 --> 00:06:16,482
I do like the little
crunchy things, though.

190
00:06:16,583 --> 00:06:18,552
If you're going to eat
something that decadent,

191
00:06:18,652 --> 00:06:19,653
it better be handmade.

192
00:06:19,753 --> 00:06:22,556
It better have a lot
of flavor to it.

193
00:06:22,656 --> 00:06:23,557
Just delicious.

194
00:06:23,657 --> 00:06:25,191
Nice job, Chef.
Thank you.

195
00:06:25,291 --> 00:06:27,093
WOMAN: It's a perfect amount
of sweetness

196
00:06:27,193 --> 00:06:29,262
with a little bit
of salty crust there.

197
00:06:29,362 --> 00:06:30,897
Like Grandma's homemade pie.

198
00:06:30,997 --> 00:06:32,833
Amazing.
Ah, come on.

199
00:06:32,933 --> 00:06:34,668
Blackberry custard
French toast.

200
00:06:34,768 --> 00:06:37,037
Wilma &amp; Frieda is one
of my favorite breakfast spots.

201
00:06:37,137 --> 00:06:38,572
Tops your day off
in a great way.

202
00:06:38,672 --> 00:06:39,806
I'm always a fan
of seeing

203
00:06:39,906 --> 00:06:41,407
brothers and sisters
work together,

204
00:06:41,508 --> 00:06:42,843
and to see that
you honor family.

205
00:06:42,943 --> 00:06:44,444
Are your grandmas
still with you?

206
00:06:44,545 --> 00:06:45,746
No.
No, they passed away.

207
00:06:45,846 --> 00:06:47,614
Did they know about
the naming?
Wilma did.

208
00:06:47,714 --> 00:06:48,815
That's why it's
Wilma &amp; Frieda's.

209
00:06:48,915 --> 00:06:50,250
Yes.
We had to put her first.

210
00:06:52,418 --> 00:06:55,255
FIERI: Next up, something's
missing at this Maui spot.

211
00:06:55,355 --> 00:06:56,523
Wow!

212
00:06:56,623 --> 00:06:59,225
But by the taste of things,
you'd never know it.

213
00:06:59,325 --> 00:07:01,234
I mean, that's the crunch
you want.

214
00:07:06,973 --> 00:07:08,942
So we're looking
for a cornmeal texture.
Where are you looking at?

215
00:07:09,042 --> 00:07:10,977
I'm looking at you
and into your eyes.

216
00:07:11,077 --> 00:07:12,312
Yes. Deep. Ah.

217
00:07:12,412 --> 00:07:15,348
♪♪♪

218
00:07:15,448 --> 00:07:17,483
You know, on
"Diners, Drive‐Ins &amp; Dives,"

219
00:07:17,584 --> 00:07:19,920
we have found great
Chinese food in Canada.

220
00:07:20,020 --> 00:07:22,488
We've also had Russian food
in Cuba

221
00:07:22,589 --> 00:07:24,958
and American barbecue
in London.

222
00:07:25,058 --> 00:07:27,628
So it's not too surprising to me
that we would come across

223
00:07:27,728 --> 00:07:29,930
a gluten‐free restaurant
here in Maui.

224
00:07:30,030 --> 00:07:31,698
This is Maui Brick Oven.

225
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:35,569
We got 2 minutes
left on the first pizzas.

226
00:07:35,669 --> 00:07:37,571
You'll never believe
that it's gluten‐free.

227
00:07:37,671 --> 00:07:39,673
I got the breaded
mozzarella sticks coming at you.

228
00:07:39,773 --> 00:07:41,174
You're not
gluten‐intolerant?

229
00:07:41,274 --> 00:07:42,108
No.

230
00:07:42,208 --> 00:07:43,309
We come here
because we love it.

231
00:07:43,409 --> 00:07:45,345
FIERI: Which is exactly
what dad‐and‐son duo

232
00:07:45,445 --> 00:07:47,781
Terry and Chad Covington
was hoping for ‐‐

233
00:07:47,881 --> 00:07:51,552
a joint losing the gluten
but keeping the flavor.

234
00:07:51,652 --> 00:07:52,819
About 6 years ago,
I found out

235
00:07:52,919 --> 00:07:54,555
I had this condition
called celiac disease.

236
00:07:54,655 --> 00:07:56,356
My son, who is a chef
on the big island,

237
00:07:56,456 --> 00:07:57,591
was also
sick with it, too,

238
00:07:57,691 --> 00:07:59,560
so we decided to open
up this restaurant

239
00:07:59,660 --> 00:08:01,467
because he can still cook
and I had something to do.

240
00:08:01,568 --> 00:08:03,704
FIERI: I had a chef on
"Guy's Grocery Games"

241
00:08:03,804 --> 00:08:07,040
that made a gluten‐free
pizza dough, and it was

242
00:08:07,140 --> 00:08:09,543
some of the best pizza
we'd ever seen on the show.

243
00:08:09,643 --> 00:08:11,845
I bet you our pizza crust will
be as good as that or better.

244
00:08:11,945 --> 00:08:13,179
Okay.
I'm down with it.

245
00:08:13,279 --> 00:08:14,715
The crust has a really
